Media notes: There were two WEWA singing at each other on both sides of the road, one downslope in a poplar forest with mountain laurel understory, the other upslope from mountain laurel on the edge of a recently-logged "shelterwood" parcel.  When I arrived, the upslope one stopped singing and began chipping.  Possibly upset at me for being too close to a nest.

Bird foraging in thicket, probing dead leaf clusters about 6-8 feet off the ground and as close as 10 feet from me. Bird was calling repeatedly long before I was within any potential alarm distance, and I walked carefully into recording range; the bird did not appear perturbed by my presence and continued foraging and calling.
Observation Details: Foraging in same exact spot where two were seen on Friday morning 16Aug2019. Calling the whole time (and well before I arrived, so not necessarily alarm calls).
